"(1)  \nThe dusk air on the Queensboro Bridge was heavy with the scent of river mist and exhaust fumes, the steel rails gleaming beneath amber streetlights reflected in their glassy surface. A dozen figures sat crammed around folding tables set atop concrete guardrails, the city’s endless expanse rumbling softly in the distance. Chandeliers—strange and temporary—cast flickering shadows across suits, dresses, and nervous faces. Someone had rented a room for the evening’s game of suspicion and secrets, and Brooklyn Ross found herself an uninvited guest, seated between two strangers whose eyes flickered more with suspicion than hospitality.\n\n(2)  \nHer host—a woman with a voice like shattered crystal—glanced at her over the rim of a crystal tumbler. “Welcome, Brooklyn. I trust you know the rules.” The clinking cutlery was more prop than functional; the real game was in the stories people chose to tell and the truths they dared to hide. Brooklyn felt the old familiar thrill, the buzz of anticipation that always came with a gathering like this, where no one was who they seemed and every word could be a clue.\n\n(3)  \nThe first accusation was levelled at $entity_1, the man in the tan overcoat who’d arrived two hours late and never explained. Someone laughed too loudly, and Brooklyn caught the fleeting tension in the woman’s hands as she reached for her napkin. Outside, a subway train rumbled, its sound magnified and distorted by the open air, as if echoing the heart of the room. The room swirled with whispered guesses and half-smirks—everyone aware that beneath the façade, the stakes were deadly.\n\n(4)  \nBrooklyn observed how $entity_2, a platinum-haired woman in a deep emerald dress, never quite met anyone’s gaze. She adjusted her cufflinks, the gesture too precise, too practiced. A man in a pinstripe suit—the designated detective, apparently—spun a tale of betrayal, but his lips betrayed uncertainty. Brooklyn noted the way the candle flames trembled in the slightest breeze, their light dancing over lies and half-truths.\n\n(5)  \nIt was during the serving of the main course, amidst the clatter and murmurs of the crowd, that the clock on the wall blinked midnight. The host’s smile was too sharp now. Someone cleared their throat. Brooklyn’s internal chronometer clicked in tandem with the external hour—this, she realized"